\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.3 Recovery Sequencing and IC Override Authority
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The IC shall ensure recovery sequencing during the security response phase follows the BIA-driven recovery sequence priority order established in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.15"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 subject to the IC's security-specific override authority defined in this section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
For the benefit of external readers:
 the BIA recovery sequence priority order determines which systems are restored first based on their criticality to County operations.
 Tier 1 (Mission Critical) systems recover first,
 followed by Tier 2 (Operationally Important),
 then Tier 3 (Administrative / Deferrable).
 Security Infrastructure —
 logging,
 monitoring,
 and vulnerability management systems —
 recovers alongside Tier 1 under security-event conditions.
 Full classification definitions are established in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.15"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
Section 6.4.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.15"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
Section 6.4 three-state rule for Security Infrastructure sequencing applies to all Chapter 4 recovery operations.
 Under Chapter 4 authority,
 every incident is a known or suspected security event by definition.
 Security Infrastructure shall therefore recover concurrently with Tier 1 systems.
 The IC shall confirm log visibility —
 that audit logging and monitoring systems are operational and producing current data —
 before authorizing broader restoration of Tier 2 and Tier 3 systems.
 This constraint ensures that systems are not returned to the environment before the Department has the detection capability to identify any residual threat activity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Before recovery execution begins,
 the IC shall establish a recovery sequencing plan documented in the work order Notes.
 The IC shall identify all systems requiring recovery,
 their tier assignments,
 and the planned restoration order in the sequencing plan.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The IC may override the standard BIA-driven recovery sequence when security considerations warrant a deviation.
 Override authority exists because the BIA recovery order is designed for operational continuity —
 it does not account for incident-specific security constraints that arise during a cybersecurity response.
 Two common scenarios illustrate when override is appropriate:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
A Tier 1 system was the point of compromise.
 Restoring it first,
 as the BIA sequence would require,
 risks reintroducing the threat vector before the environment is confirmed clean.
 The IC may defer its recovery until verification is complete on supporting systems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
A lower-tier system provides log aggregation or monitoring capability not classified as Security Infrastructure.
 The IC may elevate its recovery priority to restore detection visibility before higher-tier systems are returned to the environment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
When the IC exercises override authority,
 the IC shall document the following in the work order Notes before execution begins:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The specific deviation from the BIA recovery sequence.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The security justification for the deviation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The expected impact on RTOs for affected systems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Override authority is a security-phase authority exercised during an active incident.
 It does not modify the BIA or the 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.15"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
recovery sequence priority order.
 Upon Operational Handback,
 the 
\series bold
Policy 
