\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.6 Operational Handback
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Operational Handback is the mechanism by which the Incident Commander formally declares the security response phase complete and transfers operational recovery authority from Chapter 4 to 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.15"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
 This section governs the initiation mechanics.
 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.15"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
Section 6.7 governs the receiving obligations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The IC shall not assume Operational Handback.
 An incident remains under Chapter 4 authority until the IC explicitly declares Handback.
 Ambiguity is not permitted.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The IC shall declare Operational Handback when all of the following preconditions are satisfied:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The IC has confirmed that the eradication-complete determination has been documented under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:4.04"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
Section 6.4.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The IC has confirmed that all systems designated for recovery during the security response phase have either been returned to production with documented verification,
 or the IC has explicitly deferred them to post-Handback restoration under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.15"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
authority with documented justification.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The IC has made a documented professional judgment that no residual threat remains in the environment.
 This judgment is an IC determination,
 not a checklist item.
 It reflects the totality of the incident —
 the nature of the threat,
 the thoroughness of eradication,
 and the results of recovery verification.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The IC has confirmed that all evidence preservation obligations have been satisfied or have been transitioned to the retention framework established in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:4.02"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
Section 6.7.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The IC has triggered a postmortem review under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:4.07"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
(Postmortem Review and Lessons Learned).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The IC shall document the Operational Handback declaration in the work order Notes and Chapter 4 checklist at the time it is made.
 The IC shall reference satisfaction of each precondition in the declaration.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Upon declaring Operational Handback,
 the IC's emergency authority under Chapter 4 terminates.
 All subsequent recovery activity for systems deferred to post-Handback restoration is governed by 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.15"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
 The BIA-driven recovery sequence priority order governs any remaining restoration sequencing without IC override authority.
 Normal operational authority under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.06"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
(Operational Incident Management Policy) and 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.15"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
resumes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
A twenty-four (24) hour close-out window begins at the time of Operational Handback declaration.
 Within this window,
 the following responsible parties shall complete the following obligations:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The assigned technician shall complete all outstanding catch-up RFC documentation for recovery-phase Emergency Changes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The assigned technician shall complete all outstanding CI record updates for recovery-phase configuration changes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The IT Director shall complete CCA review for all recovery-phase Emergency Changes not yet reviewed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The Assistant IT Director shall confirm that the Chapter 4 checklist is complete for all mandatory fields through the recovery phase.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The twenty-four (24) hour close-out window governs administrative documentation obligations only.
 It does not extend IC authority.
 The IC's emergency authority terminates at the moment of Handback declaration,
 not at the expiration of the close-out window.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.7 Re-escalation to Eradication
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
If,
 during recovery operations,
 conditions are discovered that indicate the eradication was incomplete —
 including but not limited to the reappearance of threat artifacts,
 the activation of previously unidentified persistence mechanisms,
 or the observation of new 
\series bold
Indicators of Compromise
\series default
 as defined in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:4.02"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
—
 the IC shall immediately halt recovery on the affected system or systems and shall re-escalate to eradication under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:4.04"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Re-escalation is not a new incident declaration.
 The existing incident record,
 work order,
 and Chapter 4 checklist remain active.
 The IC shall document the re-escalation,
 including the conditions that triggered it,
 in the work order Notes at the time of the determination.
 Eradication recommences under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:4.04"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
authority.
 The IC shall not resume recovery under this policy until a new eradication-complete determination has been documented under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:4.04"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
Section 6.4.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
When re-escalation occurs after one or more systems have already been returned to production,
 the IC shall evaluate whether the systems already restored are affected by the newly discovered conditions.
 If the IC determines that the restored systems may be compromised,
 the IC shall direct their re-isolation under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:4.03"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
(Containment Strategy and Playbooks) authority.
 The IC shall document the re-isolation decision and the basis for it in the work order Notes.
\end_layout

